Digital literacy is the ability to use digital tools like computers and the internet to search for information, understand it, create new content, and communicate effectively in a responsible way.

More Than Just Technical Skills-

Digital literacy is not only about knowing how to operate devices. It also involves thinking critically, understanding information properly, and using it in meaningful ways.

Impact on Professional Identity -

The mention of email etiquette and maintaining a professional online presence shows that our digital behavior reflects who we are. What we do online can influence our academic and career opportunities.

Access to Advanced Learning Platforms-

Platforms like Kaggle and ResearchGate indicate that digital literacy helps individuals connect with wider academic and professional communities, enabling continuous learning and growth.

Responsibility and Ethics -

Being digitally literate also means acting responsibly. This includes respecting others online, protecting personal data, and following ethical practices while using digital platforms.

A Complete Way of Life -

The overall idea highlights that digital literacy is not limited to tools alone. It combines skills, habits, and behavior, making it an essential part of everyday life in today’s digital world.
